linkedin.blob: I was deployed to Baghdad, in 2009, as the senior system administrator for Project Liberty. This project combined advanced aircraft mounted sensor's with radio, satellite, cryptographic, and networked communications equipment. Much of this hardware and software had never been successfully made to work together in a development lab, let alone in the field. Over the course of 6 months we managed to go from a patch of dirt that was being used as a soccer field to having every feature of the project not only functional, but optimal. By the time we left the project had taken over fully 20% of the intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance data gathering in the Iraqi theater. The installation of this hardware took every bit of skill, and mental agility that the team could muster. In short it was a lot of fun! Once operational our full motion video feed was streamed live to soldiers and airmen who were actively engaged in combat. Giving them a vital advantage needed to stay alive. Server uptime was a major priority.
